    <main class="container">
        <div class="nsbir-content">
            <div class="nsbir-header">
                <div class="type-code">NSBIR</div>
                <div class="type-name">Nostalgic One</div>
                <div class="type-tagline">Steady, reflective, and quietly curious — grounded in thought and emotion</div>
            <div class="symbol-card">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-dna"></i> Symbol Breakdown</h2>
                <div class="symbol-grid">
                    <div class="symbol-item"><div class="symbol-letter">N</div><div class="symbol-text"><div class="trait">Night-aligned Chronotype</div><div class="description">Peak cognitive and emotional functioning during evening/night hours</div></div>
                    <div class="symbol-item"><div class="symbol-letter">S</div><div class="symbol-text"><div class="trait">Stable Cortisol Profile</div><div class="description">Low–moderate stress reactivity; calm and measured under pressure</div></div>
                    <div class="symbol-item"><div class="symbol-letter">B</div><div class="symbol-text"><div class="trait">Balanced Dopamine System</div><div class="description">Moderate novelty-seeking; enjoys discovery but values routine and reflection</div></div>
                    <div class="symbol-item"><div class="symbol-letter">I</div><div class="symbol-text"><div class="trait">Integrative Learning</div><div class="description">Multisensory, conceptual, and holistic learning approaches</div></div>
                    <div class="symbol-item"><div class="symbol-letter">R</div><div class="symbol-text"><div class="trait">Reward-oriented Stress-Eating</div><div class="description">May seek comforting or emotionally satisfying foods under stress</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="nsbir-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-heartbeat section-icon"></i> Biological & Neurophysiological Profile</h2>
                <p>The Nostalgic One is wired to process emotions and experiences deeply at night, with steady, controlled physiology.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Circadian Rhythm:</strong> Evening/night peak energy allows for reflective thought, creative insight, and careful planning.</li>
                    <li><strong>Stress Regulation:</strong> Stable cortisol keeps emotional reactions even; challenges are met with calm endurance rather than impulsivity.</li>
                    <li><strong>Dopamine Drive:</strong> Balanced dopamine encourages curiosity tempered with thoughtfulness—pursuing novelty without over-stimulation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Learning Modality:</strong> Integrative neural pathways support conceptual linking, visualizations, storytelling, and experiential understanding.</li>
                    <li><strong>Stress-Eating Response:</strong> Reward-oriented tendencies manifest as a desire for comfort or emotionally satisfying foods when under prolonged stress.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="nsbir-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-brain section-icon"></i> Behavioral & Cognitive Patterns</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Work Style:</strong> Deliberate, careful, and steady; excels in tasks requiring reflection, synthesis, or nuanced understanding.</li>
                    <li><strong>Decision-Making:</strong> Thoughtful, emotionally informed, and moderately cautious; avoids rash actions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Problem-Solving Style:</strong> Integrative approach; sees connections between ideas, combining logic with intuition and experience.</li>
                    <li><strong>Energy Curve:</strong> Peak insight, creativity, and reflection occur in evening and night; mornings may feel slow or introspective.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curiosity Style:</strong> Explores selectively; novelty is meaningful rather than impulsive.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="nsbir-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-users section-icon"></i> Psychological & Social Tendencies</h2>
                <div class="strengths-challenges">
                    <div class="strengths-box"><h3><i class="fas fa-star"></i> Strengths</h3><ul><li>Emotionally steady and empathetic</li><li>Reflective and thoughtful</li><li>Observant and detail-conscious</li><li>Capable of connecting ideas across contexts</li><li>Maintains focus and patience in prolonged tasks</li></ul></div>
                    <div class="challenges-box"><h3><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Challenges</h3><ul><li>May over-reflect or ruminate on past experiences</li><li>Can avoid sudden change or risk-taking</li><li>Comfort-seeking behaviors under stress may reduce proactive action</li><li>Social energy may be lower during daytime or high-activity situations</li></ul></div>
                <p style="margin-top: 24px;"><strong>Interpersonal Style:</strong> Calm, observant, and reliable companion. Offers thoughtful advice and perspective. Builds trust through consistency and empathy.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nsbir-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-compass section-icon"></i> Developmental Guidance & Growth Pathways</h2>
                <p><strong>Time & Productivity:</strong> Protect evening/night hours for creative thinking, reflection, and problem-solving. Use structured routines to anchor focus.</p>
                <p><strong>Stress Regulation:</strong> Channel reward-seeking tendencies toward constructive coping (journaling, creative outlets, meditation).</p>
                <p><strong>Emotional Growth:</strong> Embrace emotional awareness as a strength, but avoid over-attachment to nostalgia. Balance routine with occasional novelty.</p>
                <p><strong>Long-Term Potential:</strong> Thrives in creative research, analysis, strategy, counseling, mentorship, design, storytelling, planning.</p>
            </div>
